  "standardBio": "Basaltpup, titled among keepers as “Canyon Quietpaw,” carries quiet loyalty in every movement. Native to Stoneheart Canyon, the species endures through dust and canyon grit, leaving traces that other Riftlings can follow like soft maps. Wild groups form loose bonds rather than rigid packs; a calm individual may become the emotional center of a small hearthline. They eat Stonefruit eagerly and dislike food that smells of neglect or spoilage. Ancient keepers carved Basaltpup silhouettes into travel stones, believing the species guided the lost. Modern hatcheries record them as reliable companions; their practical problem-solving intelligence makes training feel like conversation. Their signature ability, Basaltpup's Canyon Edge, reflects a life shaped by Stoneheart Canyon more than by arena ambition. Many assume Basaltpups are aggressive because of their stone affinity; most are cautious first. Young Basaltpups practice Basaltpup's Canyon Edge as play long before they understand battle. Adults teach by demonstration: where to rest, what to avoid, how to share warmth or shade.",
  "fullLore": "Basaltpups first condensed from residual fossilhum along the living edges of Stoneheart Canyon after early Rift fractures cooled into weather. Their eggs appear where dust and canyon grit gathers into stillness—never in the loudest danger, always in the pocket of calm beside it. Early surveyors mistook them for ambient phenomena until a Basaltpup returned a dropped lantern, carefully, as if returning a promise.\n\nIn ancient eras, regional peoples treated Basaltpups as omen-bearers rather than pets. Carvings show them walking ahead of caravans, pausing at unstable ground, and curling around children during ashfall or fog. The species was never “tamed” in the old sense; it chose. That choice culture survives in modern Riftkeeper etiquette: you do not yank a Basaltpup into a bond. You invite, wait, and keep the invitation honest.\n\nModern history is quieter and more practical. Hatcheries map Basaltpup care cycles with the same seriousness given to rare lines, because common does not mean shallow. Stoneheart Canyon still holds wild populations that trade soft greetings with passerby pets. After major Rift events, Basaltpups often appear first at recovery centers—not as heroes, but as inventory clerks of comfort, counting who is cold, hungry, or afraid.\n\nNatural behavior is calm at the core and adaptable at the edges. They are four-footed and sure on uneven ground, companion-sized, easy to cradle, and communicate through body posture and scent marks. Socially, they prefer small trusted circles; strangers are assessed by scent, posture, and whether a keeper’s voice stays kind under stress. Intelligence presents as practical problem-solving intelligence. They sleep in moss cups and prefer weather that matches their affinity’s comfort band.\n\nEcologically, Basaltpups act as seed dispersers of calm within Stoneheart Canyon. Allies often include Canyonbeetle and Pebblit; rivalries with Veilhare and Voidling are usually about nesting space or shiny refuse, not blood feuds. Predators are rare—most threats come from collapsing terrain and careless machines rather than jaws.\n\nCulture around them is affectionate and slightly superstitious. Festival stories say the first Riftkeepers learned patience by watching Basaltpups wait out weather rather than fight it. Collectors prize unusual cosmetics, yet marketplace notes remind buyers that verified care history matters more than glitter. The common misunderstanding remains: Many assume Basaltpups are aggressive because of their stone affinity; most are cautious first. The hidden truth keepers debate in soft rooms is simpler and stranger: When deeply bonded, a Basaltpup shares short dream-images of places it has never physically visited.\n\nFrom egg to evolved form, their life story stays continuous. Eggs look like soft lantern pods veined with stone light. Hatchlings are clumsy with sincerity; adults become specialists of place; evolved stages sharpen instinct without erasing childhood habits. Battle tendencies favor swift harassment, and evolution philosophy insists transformation should answer lived experience—not fashion.\n\nFor Riftkeepers, a Basaltpup is a living chapter of Stoneheart Canyon. Feed it Stonefruit, respect its calm tempo, and it will teach you the region’s quieter grammar: which winds lie, which stones remember, which silences are safe. Personal quests often begin with a shell symbol, a remembered scent, or a dream of a door that only opens when the bond is honest. That is the Basaltpup bargain—not destiny sold at rarity price, but a life that continues because you showed up.",
